To create two KinD (Kubernetes in Docker) clusters with direct pod-to-pod connectivity on your local machine without port-forwarding, you need to ensure both clusters are attached to the same Docker network and have unique Pod/Service CIDRs.

By default, KinD clusters use 10.244.0.0/16 for pods. If both clusters use the same range, they cannot route traffic to each other because the IPs overlap.

Step 1: Create a Shared Docker Network
KinD usually creates a network called kind, but we want to be explicit to ensure both clusters land in the same subnet.

docker network create kind-mesh --subnet=172.20.0.0/16

Step 2: Define Cluster Configurations
We need to give each cluster a unique Pod Subnet and Service Subnet.

Cluster 1 Config (cluster1.yaml)

kind: Cluster
apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4
networking:
  podSubnet: "10.10.0.0/16"
  serviceSubnet: "10.11.0.0/16"
nodes:
- role: control-plane


Cluster 2 Config (cluster2.yaml)

kind: Cluster
apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4
networking:
  podSubnet: "10.20.0.0/16"
  serviceSubnet: "10.21.0.0/16"
nodes:
- role: control-plane

Step 3: Launch Clusters on the Shared Network
Set the KIND_EXPERIMENTAL_DOCKER_NETWORK environment variable so KinD puts the nodes on the network we created.

# Launch Cluster 1
KIND_EXPERIMENTAL_DOCKER_NETWORK=kind-mesh kind create cluster --name cluster1 --config cluster1.yaml

# Launch Cluster 2
KIND_EXPERIMENTAL_DOCKER_NETWORK=kind-mesh kind create cluster --name cluster2 --config cluster2.yaml

Step 4: Fix the Routing (The Secret Sauce)
Even if the nodes are on the same Docker network, Cluster 1's Node doesn't know how to reach Cluster 2's Pods (the 10.20.0.0/16 range). We must add static routes on the Docker nodes.

1. Get the Internal IP of the nodes:

C1_NODE_IP=$(docker inspect -f '{{range .NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}' cluster1-control-plane)
C2_NODE_IP=$(docker inspect -f '{{range .NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}' cluster2-control-plane)

2. Add routes across the "Bridge":

# Tell Cluster 1 how to reach Cluster 2 pods
docker exec cluster1-control-plane ip route add 10.20.0.0/16 via $C2_NODE_IP

# Tell Cluster 2 how to reach Cluster 1 pods
docker exec cluster2-control-plane ip route add 10.10.0.0/16 via $C1_NODE_IP

Step 5: Verify Connectivity
Launch a pod in Cluster 1 and try to ping the Pod IP in Cluster 2.
Launch a pod in Cluster 2 and try to ping the Pod IP in Cluster 1.
